  "text": "Our recent studies on Ringer revealed that it is expressed in embryonic, larval, and adult nervous system [CITATION_1] . We wanted to further investigate what role Ringer plays in the larval nervous system. We examined the subcellular localization of Ringer by co-staining third instar larvae with anti-Ringer (red, Figures 1A ,A -C ,C ) and the neuronal marker Hrp (green, Figures 1A ,A -C,C ). Since endogenous Ringer was expressed at very low levels, we increased the brightness of the images equally across all genotypes (Figures 1A-D ) post-imaging to evaluate Ringer expression more clearly. Ringer localized to the presynaptic NMJ terminals in the wild type ( Figures 1A ,A ) and, as expected, was absent in ringer null mutant NMJs (Figures 1B ,B ) . Upon presynaptic overexpression in elavGal4;UAS-ringer ( Figures 1C ,C ) , Ringer expression was significantly elevated in the presynaptic compartments, thus being more clearly visible at the NMJ boutons. Ringer localized close to the synaptic plasma membrane localization of Hrp ( Figures 1A ,C ) . Since Ringer is the Drosophila homolog of the human TPPP family of proteins, we next examined whether Ringer displayed any colocalization with Tubulin at the NMJ. Ringer showed endogenous expression that overlapped with Tubulin at the presynaptic NMJ terminals (Figures 1D ,D ) , while Tubulin had a much broader expression labeling MTs both of the pre-and post-synaptic larval cytoskeleton (green, Figures 1D,D ) . Ringer and Tubulin were co-stained with Hrp (blue) that labeled the presynaptic NMJ terminals ( Figure 1D ).",
